## Mandatory multi-client model

This is critical. Implémentation détaillée (guards, header client, frontend) : `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` §4.

The platform must support a user such as a fractional CIO managing several clients.

### Required concepts

* `platform_admin`: global administrator of the solution
* `client`: customer organization
* `client_user`: assignment of a user to a client with a role
* `active_client_context`: current client selected by the logged-in user

### Rules

* A platform admin can create clients, assign admins, manage subscriptions and platform-wide settings.
* A client admin can only administer their own client.
* A user may belong to multiple clients.
* Every business entity must carry a client scope.
* Every query must be filtered by authorized client IDs.
* Every write operation must validate the target client against the authenticated user scope.
* The frontend must include client context switching for authorized multi-client users.

### Minimum tables expected

* `users`
* `clients`
* `client_users`
* `roles`
* `permissions`

### Suggested minimum API

* `POST /api/platform/clients`
* `GET /api/platform/clients`
* `GET /api/platform/clients/:id`
* `POST /api/platform/clients/:id/users`
* `GET /api/me/clients`
* `POST /api/me/active-client`

---

## Backend rules (NestJS)

Structure détaillée (arborescence, modules partagés) : `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` §1 et §6.

### General structure

Organize backend code by module.

Expected folder pattern:

* `src/modules/<module-name>/`

  * `<module-name>.module.ts`
  * `<module-name>.controller.ts`
  * `<module-name>.service.ts`
  * `dto/`
  * `entities/` when useful
  * `guards/` when module-specific
  * `policies/` when useful
  * `tests/` optional depending on project organization

### Shared folders

* `src/common/` for reusable guards, decorators, interceptors, pipes, utils
* `src/config/` for configuration
* `src/prisma/` for Prisma service and helpers
* `src/auth/` for authentication flows

### Controller rules

* Controllers only handle HTTP concerns.
* No database logic in controllers.
* No complex business logic in controllers.
* Use DTOs for all inputs.
* Use explicit response shapes.

### Service rules

* Services contain business logic.
* Services must validate tenant/client scope before data access.
* Services should be small, cohesive and testable.
* Reuse shared services for finance, workflow, notifications, documents and permissions.

### DTO rules

* All write endpoints must use DTOs.
* DTOs must use class-validator decorators.
* Never accept raw unvalidated payloads.

### Prisma rules

* Prisma is the only ORM/data access layer.
* No raw SQL unless absolutely necessary.
* If raw SQL is required, isolate it and document why.
* Every model must include client scoping when it is business data.
* Prefer explicit relation names and clean schema naming.

### Authentication and authorization

* JWT access token + refresh token.
* RBAC required.
* Authorization must be enforced on every endpoint.
* Role checks must be client-aware where applicable.
* Use guards and decorators consistently.

### Auditability

* Sensitive changes must produce audit logs.
* Audit logs should capture who, what, when, target entity, target client, old/new state summary when relevant.

---

## Frontend rules (Next.js)

Structure détaillée (dossiers, contexte client) : `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` §3.

### General structure

Expected folders:

* `app/` or `src/app/`
* `components/`
* `lib/`
* `services/` or `api/`
* `hooks/`
* `types/`
* `features/` if feature-based structure is used

### UI principles

* Use TypeScript everywhere.
* Use shadcn/ui for base components when possible.
* Use Tailwind for styling.
* Keep components small and composable.
* Separate page components from business components.

### Data access

* All data access goes through API service functions.
* Never duplicate business rules in UI.
* Handle loading, error and empty states.

### Multi-client UX

* Provide a client switcher when the user has access to multiple clients.
* The active client must be visible in the UI.
* All pages and mutations must operate in the current client context.
* Never show mixed data from multiple clients unless explicitly requested and authorized in a platform-level screen.

### Admin UX

The admin studio must expose configurable interfaces for:

* modules
* fields
* reference lists
* statuses
* workflows
* roles and permissions
* dashboards
* notifications
* analytical axes

---

## API design rules

### General

* REST APIs only unless a specific exception is approved.
* Use plural resource names.
* Use predictable CRUD patterns.
* Version APIs if needed using `/api/v1/...` when project maturity requires it.

### Examples

* `/api/clients`
* `/api/budgets`
* `/api/projects`
* `/api/orders`
* `/api/suppliers`
* `/api/contracts`
* `/api/licenses`
* `/api/applications`
* `/api/databases`
* `/api/domains`
* `/api/certificates`
* `/api/telephony/numbers`
* `/api/contacts`
* `/api/documents`

### Filtering and security

* Every business endpoint must apply client filtering.
* Never trust client-provided `clientId` blindly.
* Always derive or validate it from authenticated scope.

### Idempotency

* Be careful with create/update actions on critical financial or contractual data.
* Prefer safe retry patterns for important actions.

---

## Financial core rules

The financial engine is transversal and reusable across domains.

### It must support

* budgets
* budget lines
* orders
* invoices if added later
* commitments
* consumed vs planned
* forecast
* revisions
* cost centers
* analytical axes
* suppliers
* contracts
* reporting

### Design principles

* Build one shared financial core, not one financial engine per métier.
* Connect business objects through allocations and relations.
* Keep the financial model generic and extensible.

### Typical shared entities

* `budgets`
* `budget_lines`
* `orders`
* `order_lines`
* `suppliers`
* `contracts`
* `financial_allocations`
* `cost_centers`
* `analytical_axes`
* `analytical_axis_values`

---

## Configurability rules

All configurable business behavior must be driven through an admin interface and configuration tables, not hardcoded.

### Must be configurable

* module activation
* custom fields
* field labels
* field visibility
* field required/optional status
* statuses
* workflows
* reference lists
* views and saved filters
* dashboards and widgets
* notification rules
* analytical axes
* approval chains

### Should remain controlled and not freely configurable

* security foundations
* tenant isolation rules
* low-level financial calculation integrity
* audit logging behavior
* infrastructure secrets

### Suggested config tables

* `admin_modules`
* `admin_module_fields`
* `admin_field_options`
* `admin_reference_lists`
* `admin_reference_values`
* `admin_statuses`
* `admin_workflows`
* `admin_workflow_steps`
* `admin_roles`
* `admin_permissions`
* `admin_views`
* `admin_dashboard_widgets`
* `admin_notifications`

---

## Naming conventions

### Code

* PascalCase for classes, interfaces, React component names, Prisma models
* camelCase for variables, functions and methods
* kebab-case for folders when relevant in frontend
* snake_case for database column names if mapped explicitly

### API resources

* plural nouns
* explicit domain names
* no vague endpoint names like `/data`, `/manage`, `/misc`

### File naming

* NestJS files: `<name>.controller.ts`, `<name>.service.ts`, `<name>.module.ts`
* DTOs: `create-<name>.dto.ts`, `update-<name>.dto.ts`
* React components: `PascalCase.tsx`

---

## Testing rules

### Mandatory mindset

AI-generated code is never trusted without review and test.

### Backend

* Write unit tests for services.
* Write controller tests for main endpoints.
* Cover authorization and client isolation cases.
* Cover validation failures.

### Frontend

* Test important user flows.
* Test client switching logic.
* Test form validation and permissions-dependent rendering.

### Critical tests

Always test:

* cross-client isolation
* permissions per client
* budget calculations
* contract expiration workflows
* notification triggers
* workflow transitions

---

## Performance and scalability rules

* Design queries for pagination.
* Avoid loading unnecessary relations.
* Add indexes on client-scoped foreign keys and frequent filters.
* Watch for noisy-neighbor issues in multi-tenant use cases.
* Prefer async jobs for heavy processing, imports, notifications and reports.

---

## Security rules

* Never expose secrets in code.
* Use environment variables and config modules.
* Encrypt sensitive data where needed.
* Validate file uploads.
* Sanitize document metadata and filenames.
* Enforce strict authorization at API level.
* Log security-sensitive actions.
* Never return data from another client context.

---

## Git and Cursor workflow rules

### Mandatory workflow

1. Read the relevant PRD / RFC / module spec first. For structure, repo layout, multi-client or new modules: read `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`.
2. Understand only the necessary files.
3. Plan before coding for medium or large changes.
4. Implement one bounded change at a time.
5. Generate or update tests.
6. Run tests.
7. Review diff.
8. Commit.

### Cursor usage rules

* Use Ask mode for exploration.
* Use Plan mode for medium/large features.
* Use Composer for scoped multi-file changes.
* Use Agent for implementation with test execution.
* Start new chats frequently.
* Do not keep giant conversations open for too long.
* Reference exact files and exact target behavior.

### Prompting rules

When implementing a feature, prompts should include:

* business goal
* client/tenant scope
* files to inspect
* constraints
* acceptance criteria
* required tests

### Never do

* never refactor unrelated areas without explicit request
* never remove tenant/client filters
* never weaken permissions to “make it work”
* never hardcode client-specific business logic into shared code

---

## Documentation rules

The repository must include a `docs/` folder with at least:

* **`docs/ARCHITECTURE.md`** — architecture technique (structure repo, backend/frontend, multi-client, données, logs, CI/CD)
* **`docs/VISION_PRODUIT.md`** — vision produit
* PRD, RFCs par feature
* conventions API, auth/RBAC, multi-client, admin studio

Suggested structure:

* `docs/` — ARCHITECTURE.md, VISION_PRODUIT.md à la racine
* `docs/product/` — PRD
* `docs/rfc/` — RFCs par feature
* `docs/modules/` — specs modules
* `docs/runbooks/` — opérations

---

## Module implementation expectations

When creating a new module, always define:

* business purpose
* entities
* DTOs
* API endpoints
* permissions
* client scoping rules
* workflows
* admin configurability requirements
* tests

Minimum checklist for each module:

* Prisma model(s)
* DTOs
* service
* controller
* module
* tests
* API examples
* client scoping enforced
* permissions enforced

---

## Starium Orchestra-specific product positioning

The product is not just an IT tool.
It is a configurable governance platform for support functions.

So generated code must favor:

* reusability
* modularity
* configurability
* financial transversal logic
* multi-client management
* CODIR-grade reporting readiness

---

## Definition of done

A task is done only if:

* code compiles
* tests pass
* client isolation is enforced
* permissions are enforced
* DTO validation exists
* API behavior is documented enough
* no unrelated files were modified unnecessarily
* code matches project conventions

---

## Absolute priorities

1. Tenant/client isolation
2. Security and RBAC
3. Clean modular architecture
4. Shared financial core
5. Configurable admin studio
6. Testability
7. Clear API design
8. Multi-client fractional CIO workflow

